The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Monday, July 19, 2004  Nation at a Glance				 																Haryana House BJP members resign				 																																																	Chandigarh (PTI): All the BJP members in the Haryana Assembly resigned on Sunday in protest against Punjabs termination of water-sharing agreements with its neighbouring states.				 																																																										The party has also called a statewide bandh on Monday. 				 																																																										The House members who submitted their resignations were state BJP legislature party leader Krishan Pal Gujjar, Hander Bhatia, Veena Chhibber, Vaid Kapoor Chand, Kanwar Pal Singh and Sarita Narain.				 																																																										As Assembly Speaker Satbir Singh Kadian was not in Chandigarh, the resignations were handed over to his staff here, a Vidhan Sabha spokesman said.				 																																																										Terming Punjabs step as constitutional recklessness, state BJP president Ganeshi Lal told reporters here that even the central governments inaction on the Punjab act which has insulted the Supreme Court verdict on the SYL (the Sutlej-Yamuna Link canal) issue is proof enough that chief minister Amarinder Singh had green signal of his party high command. 				 																																																										The UPA government is in league with the Amarinder Singh government on the issue, he said.				 																Fake-killing charge on BSFNew Delhi (PTI): A case of alleged fake encounter by a BSF commandant in Kashmir, purportedly to claim a gallantry medal, has come to light, sending shock waves across the establishment.				 																																																										The allegation is the second one in recent times after the allegation of fake killings in the Siachen. 				 																																																										BSF director-general Ajai Raj Sharma has ordered a court of inquiry against the officer in question, Commandant Narendra Singh, after shunting him out of Jammu and Kashmir to Mizoram, BSF sources said. 				 																																																										According to the allegations levelled by a constable, Subhash Rathore, of the 42 Battalion, a Kashmiri youth was gunned down on September 8, 2003, by the commandant and labelled a Pakistani terrorist.				 																																																										Commandant Singh himself headed the battalion.				 																																																										Rathore alleged that after the fake encounter, Singh had tried to claim the Presidents Gallantry Medal and even got a senior officer to recommend his name.				 																																																										The BSF chief said one more allegation was pending against the commandant. He added that that Singh had tried to claim a medal but it was rejected as the case could not stand the scrutiny.				 																14 killed in road crash				 																																																	Tirupati (PTI): Fourteen members of three Jain families were killed and three seriously injured when their vehicle collided with a bus at Puthalpattu, about 60 km from here, on Sunday.				 																																																										The three families, comprising 16 members, were going to the Venkateswara temple near here. They had started the journey from Nagapattinam the previous night, SP V. Gopalakrishna said.				 																																																										The bus was going from Tirupati to Tumkur in Karnataka. The driver, who was also killed, was suspected to be sleeping at the wheel, leading to the mishap, the police official said.				 																Bus falls in gorge 				 																																																	Shimla (PTI): Twelve people were killed and five injured when a bus rolled into a gorge near Kali Dhar in Chamba district on Sunday. The Himachal Road Transport Corporation bus, with 17 passengers, was on its way to Dhaman from Pathankot when the accident occurred.				 																Lawyer removed				 																																																	Ghaziabad (PTI): A general body meeting of Ghaziabad Bar Association has decided to expel Subhash Tyagi from the presidentship of the forum. The 1700-member association took the decision after Tyagi boycotted the court of additional chief judicial magistrate who had rejected the bail plea of two high court advocates who impersonated as judges. 				 																Engine jumps rails				 																																																	Nagpur (PTI): The engine of the Hatia-Kurla Lokmanya Tilak Terminus Express jumped rails after hitting a light engine while approaching Wardha station, about 80 km from here, early on Sunday morning. The engine hit the light engine, which was on the same track, while slowing its speed to halt at Wardha junction.				 																Dance bar raids				 																																																	Mumbai (PTI): Police raided eight dance bars across the metropolis and arrested nearly 120 bar girls on Saturday night. The raids were conducted in hotels located in the suburbs of Mulund, Chembur, Juhu and Dahisar, the police said. A large number of customers were also held in the raids and were released after a warning.																		President A.P.J. Abdul Kalams dream of setting up the Indian Institute of Astrophysics at Leh in Jammu and Kashmir is all set to become a reality. The state cabinet has allotted over 32,000 square feet of land for the project at Sabco in Leh.
